The paper deals with algorithmic and combinatorial optimization problems in graphs, which are central topics in computer science. The use of structural properties of the matching polytope, such as laminarity and total dual integrality, suggests that the paper may belong to the Discrete Mathematics (cs.DM) or Graph Theory (cs.GT) categories. The use of metric embeddings and graph sparsification techniques suggests that the paper may also belong to the Computational Geometry (cs.CG) or Computer Science and Game Theory (cs.GT) categories. Finally, the focus on the semi-streaming model and the use of iterative algorithms suggests that the paper may belong to the Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC) or Computational Complexity (cs.CC) categories. However, since the paper deals specifically with the maximum matching problem, which is a classic topic in algorithms and data structures, the most likely categories are Discrete Mathematics (cs.DM), Computational Complexity (cs.CC), Computational Geometry (cs.CG), Graph Theory (cs.GT), and Distributed, Parallel, and Cluster Computing (cs.DC), in that order.
